    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about bread and saw the term maillard reaction. can u explain what that actually is and what temp it usually happens at? i keep getting confused between that and caramelization.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a chemical reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars when food is heated, resulting in new flavor compounds and browning. It typically occurs at temperatures between 140°C to 180°C (284°F to 356°F), and is often referred to as the \"browning reaction.\" Unlike caramelization, which only occurs at higher temperatures (around 170°C to 200°C or 338°F to 392°F), the Maillard reaction can occur at a wider temperature range and is responsible for the characteristic flavors and colors of cooked foods, such as bread, roasted meats, and toasted bread.",
      "source": "target",
